<DOC><DOCNO> AP891002-0033 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-02-89 0253EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Poll-Questions     10-02 0964</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Poll-Questions,1007</SECOND><HEAD>With PM-Poll-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   This Media General-Associated Press poll isbased on telephone interviews Sept. 14-24 with 1,071 adults in thecontinental United States.   Phone numbers were selected randomly and interviews wereconducted with the adult who had the most recent birthday.   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in thesample. The poll has a 3-point margin of error, meaning that 19 of20 times its findings should be within 3 points of the result ifevery adult American were asked the same questions. The errormargin is larger for subgroups.   There are other sources of potential error in polls, includingthe wording and order of questions. These are the questions in thispoll; because of rounding, sums may not total 100:   1. What do you think is the most important problem facing thiscountry today? Drugs: 61 percent. Federal deficit: 5 percent.Economy: 3 percent. Environment: 3 percent. Homelessness: 3percent. Other answers: 22 percent. Don't know or no answer: 2percent.   2. (If ``drugs'') Do you think that problem will get better orworse in the next 10 years, or stay about the same? Better: 36.Worse: 44. Same: 14. DK-NA: 5.   3. Please tell me if each of the following is objectionable toyou, or not:   a. Someone growing marijuana for their own use and smoking it athome. Objectionable: 73. Not objectionable: 26. DK-NA: 1.   b. Someone buying marijuana and smoking it at home.Objectionable: 83. Not objectionable: 16. DK-NA: 2.   c. Someone selling marijuana. Objectionable: 92. Notobjectionable: 6. DK-NA: 1.   d. Someone buying cocaine and using it at home. Objectionable:96. Not objectionable: 4. DK-NA: 1.   e. Someone selling cocaine. Objectionable: 97. Notobjectionable: 3. DK-NA: 1.   4. In your opinion, how much of a problem is illegal drug use inyour neighborhood _ very serious, somewhat serious, not too seriousor not at all serious? Very: 14. Somewhat: 26. Not too: 31. Not atall: 25. DK-NA: 5.   5a. Do you personally know anyone who you believe uses cocaineor crack? Yes: 31. No: 67. DK-NA: 2.   b. (If yes) Have you ever tried to get them to stop, or not?Yes: 56. No: 44. DK-NA: 1.   c. (If yes to 5a) Do you personally know anyone who you believeis addicted to cocaine or crack? Yes: 53. No: 42. DK-NA: 5.   6. If an occasional drug user is caught with illegal drugs inhis or her car ...   a. should the car be taken away as part of the penalty? Yes: 63.No: 29. DK-NA: 8.   b. should his or her driver's license be suspended as part ofthe penalty? Yes: 82. No: 14. DK-NA: 5.   7. Should occasional drug users be sent to military-style bootcamps as punishment, or not? Yes: 47. No: 42. DK-NA: 12.   8. If a pupil is caught with drugs at school, should the school....   a. notify the parents? Yes: 99. No: 1.   b. notify the police? Yes: 78. No: 15. DK-NA: 8.   c. suspend the pupil from classes? Yes: 60. No: 31. DK-NA: 9.   d. expel the pupil from school? Yes: 26. No: 61. DK-NA: 13.   9. Do you think the federal government can or cannotsignificantly reduce the use of illegal drugs in this country? Can:65. Cannot: 29. DK-NA: 6.   10. Do you think the Bush administration is making a seriouseffort to combat illegal drug use, or not? Yes: 74. No: 20. DK-NA:6.   11a. Which of these do you think will do the most to reduce theuse of illegal drugs _ cracking down on drug producers overseas, ondrug dealers in this country, or on drug users in this country?Producers: 23. Dealers: 27. Users: 23. Equal: 21. None: 3. DK-NA: 2.   b. And which of these do you think will do more to reduce theuse of illegal drugs _ punishing drug users, or putting them intodrug treatment programs? Punish: 28. Treat: 60. DK-NA: 12.   12. To pay for federal anti-drug programs, which would youprefer _ taking money away from other programs, or raising taxes?Taking: 47. Raising: 34. DK-NA: 19.   13. A federal anti-drug effort has been proposed costing $7.9billion in the next fiscal year _ an increase of $2 billion overthis year. Do you think that's too much money, not enough, or aboutthe right amount of money? Too much: 13. Not enough: 24. Right: 39.DK-NA: 24.   14. To pay for a bigger federal anti-drug program, would yousupport or oppose:   a. Higher federal taxes on alcoholic beverages? Support: 78.Oppose: 20. DK-NA: 3.   b. Higher federal taxes on cigarettes? Support: 75. Oppose: 23.DK-NA: 2.   c. A 1 percent increase in federal personal income taxes?Support: 43. Oppose: 53. DK-NA: 4.   d. A 1 percent increase in federal corporate income taxes?Support: 70. Oppose: 25. DK-NA: 5.   15. Please tell me whether you think each of these items will orwill not reduce illegal drug use in this country:   a. Building more federal prison cells for drug offenders. Will:39. Will not: 57. DK-NA: 4.   b. Spending more federal money on drug treatment programs. Will:80. Will not: 17. DK-NA: 3.   c. Spending more federal money on drug education in schools.Will: 91. Will not: 7. DK-NA: 2.   d. Spending more federal money on military and law enforcementaid to the main cocaine exporting countries of Colombia, Boliviaand Peru. Will: 65. Will not: 26. DK-NA: 9.   16. Should President Bush order the United States armed forcesto patrol the nation's borders for drug smugglers? Yes: 82. No: 14.DK-NA: 4.   17. Should Bush order the United States armed forces to conductmilitary strikes against illegal drug operations in foreigncountries? Yes: 43. No: 46. DK-NA: 11.</TEXT></DOC>